One '''billionth''' is the [[Multiplicative inverse|reciprocal]] of a [[billion]], which means it has one of two definitions depending on whether the ''[[long and short scales|long scale]]'' or ''[[long and short scales|short scale]]'' definition is being used.<ref>{{citation|first=J. W.|last=Gardner|title=How many is a billion?|journal=[[New Scientist]]|date=April 6, 1961|department=Letters|page=888|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v4B2NNxjtloC&pg=PA888}}.</ref>
==Short scale==
In the short (or American) scale, a billionth is equal to 0.000 000 001, or 1 x 10<sup>−9</sup> in [[scientific notation]] or standard form. The prefix for this number is [[Nano-|nano]], and is abbreviated as "n" (for example, in electronics, one [[nanofarad]] would be written as 1 nF).<ref>{{citation|title=An Introduction to English Morphology: Words and Their Structure|first=Andrew|last=Carstairs-McCarthy|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|year=2002|isbn=9780748613267|pages=109–110|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yoNqhym0u2sC&pg=PA109}}.</ref>
==Long scale==
In the long (or English) scale, a billionth is equal to 0.000 000 000 001, or 1 x 10<sup>−12</sup> in [[scientific notation]] or standard form. The prefix for this number is [[pico-]], and is abbreviated as "p" (for example, in electronics, one [[picofarad]] would be written as 1 pF).<ref>{{citation|title=Dictionary of Glass: Materials and Techniques|first=Charles|last=Bray|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|year=2001|isbn=9780812236194|page=243|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KbZkxDyeG18C&pg=PA243}}.</ref>
