In [[graph theory]], the '''Kelmans–Seymour conjecture''' states that every [[k-vertex-connected graph|5-vertex-connected]] graph that is not [[planar graph|planar]] contains a [[Homeomorphism (graph theory)|subdivision]] of the 5-vertex [[complete graph]] {{math|''K''<sub>5</sub>}}. It is named for [[Paul Seymour (mathematician)|Paul Seymour]] and Alexander Kelmans, who independently described the conjecture; Seymour in 1977 and Kelmans in 1979.<ref name=Solved>{{citation|url=https://cosmosmagazine.com/mathematics/maths-mystery-solved-after-40-years|title=Maths mystery solved after 40 years|magazine=Cosmos|first=Bill|last=Condie|date=May 30, 2016}}.</ref>

By [[Kuratowski's theorem]], a nonplanar graph necessarily contains a subdivision of either {{math|''K''<sub>5</sub>}} or the [[complete bipartite graph]] {{math|''K''<sub>3,3</sub>}}.
The conjecture refines this by providing a condition under which one of these two graphs can be guaranteed to exist. In this sense, it is the analogue for [[topological minor]]s of [[Wagner's theorem]] that 4-connected nonplanar graphs contain {{math|''K''<sub>5</sub>}} as a [[graph minor]].

In 2016, a proof was claimed by Xingxing Yu of the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] and his Ph.D. students Dawei He and Yan Wang.<ref>{{Cite arxiv|last=He|first=Dawei|last2=Wang|first2=Yan|last3=Yu|first3=Xingxing|date=2015-11-16|title=The Kelmans-Seymour conjecture I: special separations|eprint=1511.05020|class=math.CO}}</ref><ref>{{Cite arxiv|last=He|first=Dawei|last2=Wang|first2=Yan|last3=Yu|first3=Xingxing|date=2016-02-24|title=The Kelmans-Seymour conjecture II: 2-vertices in $K_4^-$|eprint=1602.07557|class=math.CO}}</ref>

