Given positive integers <math>n</math> and <math>d</math>, the <math>d</math>-th '''Macaulay representation''' of <math>n</math> is an expression for <math>n</math> as a sum of [[binomial coefficient]]s:
:<math> n = \binom{c_d}{d} + \binom{c_{d-1}}{d-1} + \cdots + \binom{c_2}{2} + \binom{c_1}{1}.</math>
Here, <math>c_1,\ldots,c_d</math> is a uniquely determined, strictly increasing sequence of nonnegative integers known as the Macaulay coefficients. For any two positive integers <math>n_1</math> and <math>n_2</math>, <math>n_1 < n_2</math> if and only if the sequence of Macaulay coefficients for <math>n_1</math> comes before the sequence of Macaulay coefficients for <math>n_2</math> in [[lexicographic order]].

